profile_positions.description:
Dates (from-to): 01. 01. 2018-31. 12. 2020 (part-time);
Dates (from-to): 15. 04. 2009-01. 01. 2018 (full-time);

Main activities and responsibilities: 
Leading hardware design of neuromorphic processors; supervising PhD and MSc students on a daily basis;  research on on-chip machine learning and inference; research on energy-efficient digital/mixed-signal circuits and systems for biomedical and mobile applications; (co)-lecturing MSc courses (ET4293-Digital IC Design, and ET4054-Methods and Algorithms for System Design; responsible for the transfer of research outcomes to industry, and dissemination through peer-reviewed publications and hardware/software demonstrations.

Member of the core project team - conceptualized and described New-Contol, a €50 million EU-funded research project developing technologes to enable highly-automated vehicles; New-Control was the #2 ranked project proposal in the ECSEL call of 2018.

Research focus:
Developing energy-efficient solutions for high-performance, mobile and ubiquitous micro- and nano-systems following four energy-centric research thrusts that cover the entire range from physical sensing to data sense-making:
- enabling energy-efficient data sense-making via innovative approaches to embed on-chip machine learning and inference;
- enabling sensor fusion/cognition acceleration via innovative bionic signal processors;
- circuit- to system-level techniques to enhance the energy-efficiency of VLSI circuits to enable continued performance enhancements under a tight power budget (including ultra-low power read-out circuits, digital signal processing, power management, cognitive systems); 
- reliability management and error-resilient VLSI circuits and systems.

(Co)-Lecturing:
1. ET4293 - MSc level course, Digital IC Design;
2. ET4054 - MSc level course, Methods and Algorithms for System Design.

Position held:  01.06.2005-30.08.2006; Senior Research Scientist, Project Leader; 
Position held:  01.11.2000-01.06.2005; Research Scientist;

Main activities and responsibilities: Research and development of circuit techniques and algorithms for power-efficient mixed-signal circuit design and test; delivering transferable results within the company; leading R&D team of a five full-time employees and supervising PhD students on a daily basis; developing product roadmap.
